\fs46 \cf2 \ul How do I get rid of Wi-Fi interference?
\b \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\sa321\partightenfactor0

\b0\fs28 \cf2 \
Your router uses radio signals, which can be interrupted by other electrical appliances in your home. Microwaves, Bluetooth devices, cordless phones, fridges and baby monitors are some of the most common culprits. So try and keep your router away from them.\
If you\'92re getting a lot of problems when you use a cordless phone, you might need to get one that broadcasts on a higher frequency. Before you buy one, tell the retailer about the problem you\'92re having, so they can advise you on the best phone.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl720\sa44\partightenfactor0

\fs46 \cf2 \ul How do I get the best from my Wi-Fi channel?
\b \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\sa321\partightenfactor0

\b0\fs28 \cf2 \
For 2.4GHz Wi-Fi routers there are 13 channels for Wi-Fi in the UK, each giving a slightly different frequency. You\'92ll only be connected to one, so the others can sometimes disturb your connection.\
So, how does your router decide which one to connect to? Well, it\'92ll usually try to choose the one being used the least in the area.\
The new Plusnet Hub One router is even cleverer. It uses dual-band Wi-Fi, which means it connects to two different frequencies, to give you an even stronger Wi-Fi signal.\
Get the best from your new Hub One router by using devices alongside it which work on 5GHz. Newer computers should work fine, but older machines might need a bit of upgrading. You can do this easily using a dual-band USB dongle. Have a look at our\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dillinger.io/help/broadband/router-user-guides/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 router guides}}\'a0for a bit more on this.\
If you\'92re having problems with any router, you should check it\'92s connected to a channel that\'92s as free as possible. There are ways to check how many routers are using the same channel as you, have a look on our\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://community.plus.net/forum/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 forums}}\'a0for more info. If, when you look, your router is using a channel with a lot of routers on it, you\'92ll be better off changing to a less common one. Channel one, six or eleven will usually give you the best speed.\
